12 information. Upon proof that proper notice has been given, existing law authorizes
13 a court of competent jurisdiction to order the animal sold at auction, humanely
14 destroyed or continued in the care of the officer. (NRS 574.055) Sections 1.2 and 3
15 of this bill reorganize these provisions. Section 1.2 further requires that, in a county
16 whose population is 100,000 or more (currently Clark and Washoe Counties), if an
17 officer takes possession of an animal being treated cruelly and determines that
18 immediate humane euthanasia of the animal may be necessary, a licensed
19 veterinarian must examine the animal and recommend the humane euthanasia of the
20 animal before the humane euthanasia may proceed. Section 14 of this bill makes a
21 conforming change to provide that a pet removed from a motor vehicle under
22 certain circumstances is an animal being treated cruelly for the purposes of taking
23 possession of the animal under section 1.2.
24 Section 3 removes the authorization for a court to order the animal sold at
25 auction.
26 Existing law provides that, with certain exceptions, the seizure and disposition
27 of an animal which an officer discovers is being treated cruelly does not apply to
28 any animal which is located on land being employed for an agricultural use. (NRS
29 574.055) Section 3 removes this exception.
30 Existing law provides that a person who engages in certain acts of torture or
31 cruelty to animals is guilty of a misdemeanor for a first offense, except if the
32 person: (1) willfully and maliciously engages in such an act, the person is guilty of
33 a category D felony; or (2) commits the act to threaten, intimidate or terrorize
34 another person, the person is guilty of a category C felony. (NRS 574.100) Section
35 1.4 of this bill provides instead that certain acts related to torture or the unjustifiable
36 maiming, mutilating or killing of certain animals is subject to enhanced penalties as
37 follows: (1) a knowing or reckless violation is a category D felony; (2) a willful and
38 malicious violation is a category C felony; (3) committing the act to threaten,
39 intimidate or terrorize another person is a category B felony, punishable by
40 imprisonment in the state prison for a minimum term of 1 year and a maximum
41 term of 6 years. Additionally, section 1.4 provides that the following willful and
42 malicious violations are subject to enhanced penalties: (1) restraining a dog in
43 certain manners is, with certain exceptions, a gross misdemeanor; (2) abandoning
44 an animal in certain circumstances is a category C felony; and (3) committing
45 certain acts of animal cruelty to an animal which causes the death of the animal is a
46 category B felony, punishable by imprisonment in the state prison for a minimum
47 term of 1 year and a maximum term of 6 years and a fine of not more than $10,000.
48 Sections 10, 12, 13 and 15, respectively, of this bill provide that a person who
49 has received an enhanced sentence for such acts of animal cruelty: (1) may not
50 receive a deferred judgment from the court; (2) is subject to a maximum period of
51 probation or suspension of a sentence of 60 months; (3) is not eligible for the
52 Division of Parole and Probation of the Department of Public Safety to petition a
53 court to recommend the early discharge of the person from probation; and (4) is not
54 eligible to have certain credits deducted from the minimum term or minimum
55 aggregate term imposed by his or her sentence of judgment.
56 Section 4 of this bill provides that it is an affirmative defense to a violation of
57 certain acts of animal cruelty if the person reasonably believes that the person was
58 engaging in the reasonable discipline of the animal.
59 Existing law provides that a person who engages in certain acts of torture of or
60 cruelty to a police animal is guilty of: (1) a category D felony if the police animal is
61 not totally disabled or killed; and (2) a category C felony if the police animal is
62 totally disabled or killed. (NRS 574.105) Section 5 of this bill increases these
63 penalties to a category C felony if the police animal is not totally disabled or killed
64 and a category B felony if the police animal is totally disabled or killed.
65 Existing law prohibits the owner, possessor or person in charge or custody of a
66 maimed, diseased, disabled or infirm animal from abandoning the animal, leaving
