67 the animal to die in certain public places or allowing the animal to lie in certain
68 public places for more than 3 hours after the person receives notice that the animal
69 is left disabled. A violation of this prohibition is a misdemeanor. (NRS 574.110)
70 Section 5.5 of this bill instead prohibits the intentional abandonment or leaving to
71 die of any animal, including a maimed, diseased, disabled or infirm animal, by such
72 a person and makes a violation of this prohibition a gross misdemeanor.
73 Existing law sets forth the applicability of certain provisions relating to cruelty
74 to animals. (NRS 574.200) Section 6 of this bill provides that these provisions do
75 not prohibit the humane euthanasia of an animal by a veterinarian, veterinarian
76 technician or euthanasia technician if such a person determines that humane
77 euthanasia is necessary to end the intractable suffering of an animal.
78 Existing law requires that if a person is lawfully arrested for certain crimes
79 against animals and an animal owned or possessed by the person is impounded by
80 the county, city or other local government in connection with the arrest, the person
81 must be notified of his or her right to request a hearing within 5 days. If the person
82 does not request a hearing, or if the owner of the animal has not been identified
83 within 5 days after the arrest, the county, city or other local government which
84 impounded the animal is required to transfer ownership of the animal to an animal
85 rescue organization, animal shelter or another person who is able to provide
86 adequate care and shelter to the animal. (NRS 574.055, 574.203) Sections 3 and 7
87 of this bill require the owner to be notified of his or her right to request a hearing
88 within 5 business days after receiving the notice. Sections 3 and 7 also provide
89 that, if the arrested and detained person does not request a hearing, or the owner of
90 the animal has not been identified within 5 business days after the arrest, the animal
91 must be forfeited to the county, city or other local government which took
92 possession of the animal, who must then dispose of the animal as the county, city or
93 other local government sees fit.
94 Section 1.8 of this bill requires a court to order a person convicted of certain
95 unlawful acts of animal cruelty to pay restitution for all costs associated with the
96 care, impoundment and disposition of the animal of which a county, city or other
97 local government takes possession.
98 Existing law provides that the knowing, purposeful or reckless killing or
99 injuring of an animal may be an act that constitutes domestic violence. (NRS
100 33.018) Existing law authorizes a court, by a temporary order, to enjoin the adverse
101 party named in an application for an order for protection against domestic violence
102 from: (1) physically injuring, threatening to injure or taking possession of any
103 animal that is owned or kept by the applicant for the order or a minor child and any
104 animal that is owned or kept by the adverse party; and (2) physically injuring or
105 threatening to injure any animal that is owned or kept by the adverse party. Existing
106 law further authorizes the court, by extended order, to specify arrangements for the
107 possession and care of any animal owned or kept by the adverse party, applicant or
108 minor child. (NRS 33.030) Section 8 of this bill authorizes the court, by temporary
109 order, to enjoin the adverse party from taking possession of an animal that is owned
110 or kept by the adverse party.
111 Existing law requires, if a child is adjudicated delinquent for an unlawful act
112 that involves cruelty to or torture of an animal, the juvenile court to order the child
113 to participate in counseling or other psychological treatment. (NRS 62E.680)
114 Sections 1.9 and 9 of this bill require the juvenile court to order such a child to also
115 undergo a psychological evaluation.
116 Existing law provides that if a person is convicted for an unlawful act involving
117 animal cruelty, a court may order, as a condition of probation, the person to submit
118 to a psychiatric evaluation and participate in counseling or therapy. (NRS
119 176A.416) Sections 1.9 and 11 of this bill authorize a court to also order such a
120 person to participate in a rehabilitative or educational program.
